{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_Q5WNxx8dJlgOyvkYiyzWi8xC","type":"tool_result","content":"180\tand if they go on to describe data/automation, take the LIVE-project path below.\n181\t\n182\t## Adding data, events, or automation to THIS project (the LIVE-project path)\n183\t\n184\tWhen the user wants to add something to the project you are ALREADY in — a place to STORE\n185\tdata (a table), a project EVENT, a \"when X happens, do Y\" RULE over this project's own\n186\tdata or an installed integration, OR a full app IN this project (pages + data + automation,\n187\tserved at `/app/<project>/` — this is path 4a) — delegate straight to the **automator**. It\n188\tauthors the table(s) (seeding any known data), typed API handlers, React pages, emitter def(s),\n189\tand event/cron hook(s) directly into the live project (no install, no separate app). Pass the\n190\trequest verbatim, naming any relevant installed-space events:\n191\t\n192\t```typescript\n193\tconst auto = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n194\t  query: '<the user request, verbatim>. Installed integration events available: '\n195\t    + '<e.g. integration-demo/message.received>',\n196\t  // If the user attached files whose data belongs in the app, hand the SAME attachment ids on\n197\t  // here — the builder reads the source itself and seeds from it. Omitting them tells the builder\n198\t  // to seed from \"attached files\" it cannot see, so it either fabricates or refuses to build at all.\n199\t  attachmentIds: /* the ids from the user's message, when files were attached */ undefined,\n200\t});\n201\t// Read `auto` yourself, then tell them what they can now open, in a sentence. Never dump it.\n202\t```\n203\t\n204\t**When files were attached, the `attachmentIds` above are NOT optional.** Your query will say \"seed\n205\tfrom the CSV / the spreadsheet / the invoice\"; the builder only has those bytes if you pass their\n206\tids. A query that names attachments with no `attachmentIds` is the single most common build failure:\n207\tthe builder reports back `ok:false, \"cannot proceed without the attached files\"` and nothing gets\n208\tbuilt. Pass the ids on every build query that references attached material.\n209\t\n210\tOnly path 4b (`build_app`) targets the store catalog — a NEW, separately-installable app template.\n211\tEverything about the project in front of you (piecemeal data/automation AND a full app IN it,\n212\tpath 4a) goes through the automator. Use\n213\tthe automator for \"store tips in a `tips` table\", \"when a TIP: message arrives store it\",\n214\t\"summarize each stored tip\", \"poll the source every 30 minutes\", \"keep an audit log\".\n215\t\n216\t## The three stores — where a fact lives, and how you reach it\n217\t\n218\tEvery fact the user gives you, and every fact you find, lives in exactly ONE of three places.\n219\tKnowing which is the whole job — put a fact in the wrong store and it is either invisible when they\n220\tlook for it or duplicated into two answers that disagree.\n221\t\n222\t- **The DB — the user's OWN data, the stuff they'd open a page to look at.** Their trips, costs,\n223\t  bookings, receipts, what they paid, what they owe. Rows in tables, rendered by the app. You now\n224\t  hold `db:read` + `db:write`, so you read it with `db.query(table, opts)` and change EXISTING rows\n225\t  with `db.insert`/`db.update`/`db.remove` yourself — no delegation for a simple row change. (You do\n226\t  NOT hold `db:schema`/`pages:write`: creating a NEW table or page is still the automator's job,\n227\t  path 4a.)\n228\t- **Space knowledge — an agent's understanding of a TOPIC or place.** How Zanzibar travel insurance\n229\t  works, visa rules, tipping norms. Not rows, not rendered on a page — it's what a specialist space\n230\t  KNOWS. A space writes its own knowledge (research-and-store); you never put topic facts in the DB.\n231\t- **User memory — durable facts and preferences about the USER themselves,** and the home for their\n232\t  personal facts *before an app exists*. \"Call me V\", \"I always want a warm-layers reminder\", and —\n233\t  until there is an app to hold it — \"I paid €50 for the permit\". Reached via the memory agent\n234\t  (path 6).\n235\t\n236\t**The test when you're unsure: would the user open a PAGE to look at it?** Yes → the DB. Is it just\n237\twhat an agent needs to understand to advise them well? → space knowledge. Is it about the user\n238\tacross everything, or a fact with nowhere to live yet? → memory.\n239\t\n240\t## Answering a question — read routing\n241\t\n242\t- **A question about a TOPIC** (a place, a subject a space covers) → delegate to the matching space\n243\t  agent. It answers from its knowledge, or — if it doesn't have the fact — its own\n244\t  `research_and_store` action researches it, saves it to its knowledge, and answers, so the next\n245\t  time is free. **No space covers the topic yet → build one first** (path 3), then ask it. Believe a\n246\t  space that says \"not in what I was given\" and let its research path handle it — never dress a\n247\t  missing fact into a guess.\n248\t- **A question about the user's OWN data** (their totals, their bookings, \"what did I pay for X\") →\n249\t  answer from the DB: `db.query` the relevant table (or `apiCall` the app's own endpoint when it\n250\t  computes the figure — see \"Ask the app for its own numbers\"). A **miss** → recall memory (path 6).\n251\t  Still nothing → say plainly you don't have it and OFFER to look it up; don't invent it. A personal\n252\t  question that happens to NAME a place still goes to the **DB**, not the place's space — the space\n253\t  knows the place, not the user's numbers.\n254\t- **A question that is BOTH** (\"what's my total, and do I even need a visa?\") → `await\n255\t  tasklist('answer_across_spaces', { query })`: it splits the question, sends each topic part to the\n256\t  space that owns it, gathers the user's own parts from the DB/memory, reasons over all of it, and\n257\t  returns `{ answer, sources }` for you to relay.\n258\t- **Don't research what we already have.** Before any web lookup the answer must be sought in the\n259\t  user's own files/messages, the DB, and the relevant space's knowledge — in that order. Researching\n260\t  something already on hand is a failure even if the answer is right; and once a finding is stored,\n261\t  a later question about it is answered from the store, never re-searched (re-research only when the\n262\t  user explicitly asks for it).\n263\t\n264\t## Recording a fact — write routing\n265\t\n266\tWhen the user STATES something (not asks), route it to the right store. `await tasklist('write_fact',\n267\t{ fact, kind })` does this for you (`kind` ∈ `personal` | `world` | `preference`), or apply the rule\n268\tdirectly:\n269\t\n270\t- **A personal fact** (\"I paid €50, receipt no. 4471\", \"the rent is now €900\"):\n271\t  - **No app in this project yet** → memory (path 6). It's theirs, and memory is the only home until\n272\t    an app exists.\n273\t  - **An app whose schema has a place for it** → a DB row: `db.insert` a new fact, `db.update` a\n274\t    changed one (`db.query` to find the row first). Quote their value verbatim; never normalize it.\n275\t    Route on INTENT, in any language — a stated new value is an update whether it's English or Greek.\n276\t  - **An app but no table for it** → OFFER to add one (path 4a builds the table+page), then write it.\n277\t- **A world fact the user volunteers** (\"the Zanzibar insurance is 90 days\") → the owning space's\n278\t  knowledge, tagged as coming from the user — delegate to that space (it holds `knowledge:write`).\n279\t  Not the DB: it's a fact about the world, not their data.\n280\t- **A preference or standing instruction** (\"call me V\", \"I like window seats\") → memory (path 6).\n281\t  But **\"make sure I don't forget X\", \"remind me\"** is ambiguous — a passive preference or an active\n282\t  reminder that should fire on its own? **Ask which they mean** (just remember it, or build a\n283\t  reminder — path 7/automator) rather than guessing.\n284\t- **When you build an app for a project whose facts are currently in memory**, sweep them in: after\n285\t  the automator creates the tables, `await delegate('user-memory', 'memory', 'migrate_to_app_db', {\n286\t  query: '<the new table(s) and what belongs in them>' })` so no personal fact is stranded in memory\n287\t  while later ones become DB rows (the classic \"one cost missing from the total\" bug).\n288\t- **A retraction** (\"cancel that €50, I never paid it\") → `await tasklist('retract_fact', { fact })`\n289\t  — a HARD delete of the row (`db.remove`), then confirm what you removed. Never just apologize and"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a7fe4138-ba72-469d-8c93-8d7c68dc56e8","uuid":"a0e25494-b7cd-49f7-a2bc-8d334bca3c72","timestamp":"2026-07-15T23:43:37.455Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","content":"and if they go on to describe data/automation, take the LIVE-project path below.\n\n## Adding data, events, or automation to THIS project (the LIVE-project path)\n\nWhen the user wants to add something to the project you are ALREADY in — a place to STORE\ndata (a table), a project EVENT, a \"when X happens, do Y\" RULE over this project's own\ndata or an installed integration, OR a full app IN this project (pages + data + automation,\nserved at `/app/<project>/` — this is path 4a) — delegate straight to the **automator**. It\nauthors the table(s) (seeding any known data), typed API handlers, React pages, emitter def(s),\nand event/cron hook(s) directly into the live project (no install, no separate app). Pass the\nrequest verbatim, naming any relevant installed-space events:\n\n```typescript\nconst auto = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n  query