ial Park Fees (NCAA Tariffs, non-East African citizens)\\\",\\n            detail: \\\"From the ngorongoro-conservation-area-tariffs.pdf and trip-costs.xlsx: Entry permit is $70.80 per non-EA adult (age 16+). Crater service fee is $70.80 per non-EA adult. Crater vehicle descent fee is $295.00 per vehicle/trip (non-EA). These three line items are reflected in the costs sheet: entry $141.60 (2 pax × $70.80), crater service fee $141.60 (2 pax × $70.80), vehicle descent $295.00. Camping fees (public campsite) are $35.40 per non-EA adult 16+; special campsite is $70.80. However Vasilis's safari package uses Jevas Hotel (HB) at the rim, not camping inside the crater. Only 4×4 vehicles up to 3,500 kg tare weight are allowed on the crater floor. Crater descent gates close at 16:00; all visitors must exit by 18:00. Speed limit is 25 kph at the crater. A licensed guide or NCAA ranger must accompany all crater visitors. Off-road driving is prohibited. A maximum of 5 vehicles at an animal sighting. Ngorongoro nights are cold — warm layers needed (per markdown notes).\\\"\\n          },\\n          {\\n            heading: \\\"Crater-Day Experience (Voice Memo + Specialist Facts)\\\",\\n            detail: \\\"The crater day was described as 'one of the best days of my life' — wildlife everywhere, up close. The driver/guide was Emmanuel (not Richard from the Suricata office), described as very knowledgeable, spotting wildlife before they even came into view. At the rim, on the way out, a Maasai lady was selling beaded bracelets. Vasilis bought two for Athina Mari. The asking price was $25 or $20 for both (uncertain recall); he paid roughly 35,000 TZS in shillings. Emmanuel mentioned an extra ranger tip expected at the gate: ~5,000 TZS cash, separate from park fees — something nobody told them about beforehand.\\\"\\n          },\\n          {\\n            heading: \\\"Open Questions / Reminders\\\",\\n            detail: \\\"Ask Richard whether the ranger tip (~5,000 TZS) is legitimate/expected, before settling the safari balance payment ($960 USD). The exact bracelet purchase amount is uncertain (roughly 35,000 TZS ≈ $20–25 USD); should be recorded as an estimated expense with a note. NCAA rules: only designated Cultural Bomas permit photography of local people; the Maasai bracelet purchase at the rim may fall outside that — worth noting.\\\"\\n          },\\n          {\\n            headi\n--- 207 llm_request fork:build_specialist","numLines":25,"startLine":1,"totalLines":201}}}
